      "heading": "Patriotic Standardization and Institutional Rigidity: \"America, America\"",
      "text": "Unlike the highly malleable, parodic folk songs that dominate the vast majority of the campfire repertoire, nationalistic and patriotic anthems are treated with strict reverence and structural rigidity by the institutions that run these camps. The song \"America the Beautiful,\" alongside its round-based adaptations, highlights how institutional guidelines constrain the natural folk process in order to preserve ideological consistency.  \nThe lyrics of \"America the Beautiful\" were originally penned as a poem in 1893 by Katharine Lee Bates, an English professor at Wellesley College, following an awe-inspiring, cross-country trip to the summit of Pikes Peak in Colorado.78 She revised the poem formally in 1904 and 1911, and it was eventually paired inextricably with a hymn composed earlier in 1882 by New Jersey organist Samuel A. Ward titled \"Materna\".78 While the first verse famously extols the physical majesty of the nation (\"purple mountain majesties, above the fruited plain\"), ethnomusicologists and historians note that subsequent verses were intended as a harsh, progressive critique of the Gilded Age's robber barons. Bates was warning against the corruption of massive wealth, pleading: \"America\\! America\\! God shed his grace on thee. Till selfish gain no longer stain, The banner of the free\\!\".81 The song's cultural footprint is massive, extending from elementary school classrooms to the emotional use of Ray Charles's rendition in the Season 4 premiere of the television show *Outlander*.79  \nIn the context of modern youth camps, particularly the Boy Scouts of America, the organization enforces strict rules against the lyrical alteration or parodic subversion of this specific song. Official Cub Scout guidelines mandate that \"To encourage citizenship and respect for patriotic ideals, the lyrics to the following patriotic songs should not be changed: 'America,' 'America the Beautiful,' 'God Bless America,' and 'The Star-Spangled Banner'\".82 Thus, the folk process of *contrafactum*—which we have seen applied to almost every other melody in the repertoire—is explicitly banned here by institutional decree in order to maintain a specific civic atmosphere.82  \nHowever, the acoustic constraints of the camp environment still find ways to adapt patriotic fervor into its specific musical structures without altering the sacred text. A secondary song, identified in 4-H and Sanborn camp songbooks simply as \"America, America,\" utilizes the classic round format to foster group participation without requiring instrumentation: \"America, America, shall we tell you how we feel? You have given us your spirit (or riches), We love you so\".83 By creating a simpler, cyclical round, camps maintain the thematic reverence of Bates' work while employing a musical structure more conducive to an outdoor, unaccompanied acoustic setting. Both Bates' original lyrics and Ward's melody are firmly in the public domain, though modern specific arrangements or mechanical recordings may hold distinct copyrights.78"
