      "heading": "Scatological Subversion vs. Vesper: \"The Birdie Song\"",
      "text": "\"The Birdie Song\" represents one of the most fascinating dichotomies in the entire camp repertoire, existing simultaneously as a serene, innocent lullaby and a gross-out, scatological humor song, depending entirely on the age group and context in which it is sung.  \nIn its innocent form, typically sung to younger campers, Daisies, or as an evening vesper to calm the group before bed, the lyrics beautifully describe resting nature: \"Way up in the sky, the big birdies fly. While down in the nest, the little birds rest. With a wing on the left, and a wing on the right, the little birds sleep, all through the night\".70 This iteration relies on soft vocalizations, culminating in the singers loudly \"shushing\" the audience so as not to wake the birds, before cheerfully proclaiming the arrival of morning (\"The bright sun comes up, the dew falls away\").71  \nConversely, the older camper demographic utilizes a completely different, highly subversive lyrical set known as \"Birdie Birdie in the Sky.\" This version relies entirely on the shock value of avian defecation: \"Birdie birdie in the sky, why do you do that in my eye? I will not laugh, I will not cry, I'm just glad that pigs don't fly\".73 This iteration serves as a cumulative volume chant, introducing the classic camp bridge: \"Second verse, same as the first. A little bit louder and a little bit worse,\" before repeating the lyrics at a significantly higher decibel level.74 The final verse usually substitutes \"pigs\" with cows, and eventually with the name of a specific camp counselor (\"I'm just glad that counselor \\[Name\\] don't fly\"), turning the scatological humor into a direct, affectionately sanctioned insult toward authority figures.73 Other variations include complex nonsense names for the bird, such as \"Ogga-flogga-fleega-flogga-ishka-nishka-nog ga-nogga-ogga-flogga\" to test memory.75  \nThis dual existence brilliantly demonstrates how a single thematic anchor—birds in the sky—can be manipulated by oral tradition to serve completely opposing sociological functions: pacification for the very young, and rebellious, boundary-testing camaraderie for the older youth. Both versions are deeply entrenched in the oral tradition and lack any formal copyright restrictions.76"
