      "heading": "The Subversion of Institutionalization and Macabre Humor: \"Here Comes My Wagon\"",
      "text": "\"Here Comes My Wagon\" represents a highly specific and fascinating subcategory of the campfire repertoire: the subversive nonsense song. Unlike anthems that promote group unity, patriotism, or physical coordination, this piece operates entirely on the psychological premise of dark humor, specifically addressing themes of madness, institutionalization, and societal exile.  \nThe lyrics typically follow a repeating, cyclical cadence that mimics the sound of an approaching vehicle: \"Ding, ding, ding, ding, ding, Here comes my wagon, my wagon, I hear the keeper calling me\".16 The narrative voice of the song happily and un-ironically anticipates being taken away to the \"funny factory\" (a mid-century colloquialism for an inpatient psychiatric hospital), concluding with the self-deprecating rationalization: \"Just like all the nuts that fall, I'm a little cracked that's all\".16 The final verse usually escalates the absurdity by swapping the wagon for a \"kiddie car\" or a \"truck,\" ending with a jubilant shout of \"Whooopeeeee\\!\".16  \nThe underlying ethnomusicological trend here is the use of the campfire space as a safe, socially sanctioned environment for youth to explore taboo subjects. The rigid, highly structured environment of a summer camp—with its constant supervision, bugle calls, and cabin inspections—often subconsciously mimics institutionalization for the youth attending. Singing cheerfully about a \"keeper\" and a \"wagon\" taking one away provides a satirical, cathartic release from the pressures of this regimented conformity.16  \nFolklorists have long recognized the immense cultural value of this subversive subgenre. \"Here Comes My Wagon\" is formally documented in the Jack Horntip Collection of field recordings, an archive dedicated to preserving the unvarnished oral traditions of youth. In this archive, it is categorized under customary and humorous camp songs, sitting alongside other macabre campfire chants such as \"Poor Rose She Died\" and the \"Ugly Cadence\".18 These archives also note other deeply macabre songs adjacent to this tradition, such as the chant about finding a \"yellow bill\" bird, taking it in, and casually crushing its head to have a feast, or the song about a buffalo lying dead in the sand \"since way last May\".17  \nThe melody of \"Here Comes My Wagon\" is a simple, jaunty tune that contrasts incredibly sharply with the dark thematic content, a structural feature highly common in children's macabre folklore to make the horrific palatable. Archival records from the Orbis Cascade Alliance classify the piece as an undated child and young adult cumulative round song.19 Copyright for \"Here Comes My Wagon\" does not exist in any commercial registry; it is a true folk artifact. It survives in Girl Scout and Boy Scout camps across North America, enduring precisely because its slight, cheerful subversion of authority appeals heavily to the adolescent desire to break social decorum.17"
