      "heading": "Digital Virality and the Evolution of \"The Llama Song\"",
      "text": "The evolution of \"The Llama Song\" highlights the modern friction between digital internet culture and traditional acoustic oral transmission. There are two primary lineages of the \"Llama Song\" referenced in modern camp settings, and understanding their divergence is crucial to contemporary ethnomusicology.  \nThe first lineage is the purely physical, unpitched camp chant. Participants use their hands to physically form a \"llama\" (raising the index and pinky fingers to form ears, while pressing the middle and ring fingers against the thumb to form a snout).54 The song requires the singer to rapidly articulate different emotional states of the llama while manipulating their hand puppet to match. Actions include \"Happy llama\" (held upright), \"Sad llama\" (pointing the hand down), \"Super llama\" (scooping the hands upward as if flying), \"Drama llama\" (making two hand-llamas kiss), and finally culminating in non-llama entities like \"Moose\" (placing fingers spread apart on the head like antlers) or \"Turkey\".54 This version is usually chanted rhythmically without a distinct melody, serving as a rapid-fire cognitive and dexterity test as the speed incrementally increases to world-record paces.55  \nThe second lineage is highly melodic and deeply tied to late-20th-century pop music and early-2000s internet viral culture. One documented camp variation borrows heavily from stadium arena rock, utilizing the iconic stomp-clap beat of Queen's \"We Will Rock You\" for the verses and the instantly recognizable melody of Steam's \"Na Na Hey Hey Kiss Him Goodbye\" for the chorus (\"Llama llama, llama llama, I ride a, ride a llama\").56 Another highly prevalent version features lyrics such as: \"Here's a llama, there's a llama, and another little llama, fuzzy llama, funny llama, llama llama duck\".57 This specific absurd lyrical string originates directly from a viral 2004 Flash animation created by Burton Earny (under the moniker AlbinoBlackSheep).57  \nThe seamless integration of a viral internet animation into the acoustic campfire repertoire proves that the folk process is not dead; rather, its source material has simply shifted from radio broadcasts and music halls to digital media. While the original Flash animation and its specific audio track are copyrighted by its creator, the physical \"happy llama/sad llama\" hand-chant and the Queen/Steam mashups operate organically as public domain playground games and fair-use parodies, respectively.54"
