    "id": "song-one-fat-hen",
    "title": "One Fat Hen",
    "tune": "Spoken",
    "setting": "Logs",
    "energy": "rowdy",
    "notes": "Every camp does this a little different. This is Lawton’s variation. It’s fun to get good at it and then watch the audience squirm as you wait for them to repeat you.",
    "actions": [],
    "lyrics": "*Start with the first line, repeat adding the next line each time till at the end you’re doing all 10 in one run.*  \nOne Fat Hen  \nAnd a couple of ducks  \nThree baby brown bears  \nFour rabbit running hares  \nFive feisty felines frolicking in the forest  \nSix simple Simons selling salt in Siam  \nSeven slimy sailors sniffing snoots  \nEight elongated elephants elevating on an escalator  \nNine nasty-nosed Nimbrios nibbling on nine nasty-nosed Nimbriots   \nAnd   \nTen two-ton two-toned transcontinental trucks traveling from Tallahassee, Tennessee to Tyler, Texas on two tanks of True Test Texaco and twenty-two terrible tires\\!",
    "background": {
      "heading": "Cognitive Diction Tests and Social Equalization: \"One Fat Hen\"",
      "text": "\"One Fat Hen,\" which is frequently extended to the title \"One Fat Hen and a Couple of Ducks,\" operates as a rigorous cumulative memory game and diction exercise disguised as a campfire song. Functioning primarily in a strict \"repeat-after-me\" or call-and-response format, it requires a designated leader to recite increasingly lengthy and linguistically complex lines, which the audience must perfectly echo back in unison.10  \nThe history of \"One Fat Hen\" is particularly fascinating, as it traces its origins not to traditional acoustic music, but rather to its use as a mid-twentieth-century announcer's test for radio broadcasters. The sequence was explicitly designed by vocal coaches to test breath control, precise enunciation, and short-term memory recall under pressure. It was subsequently adopted by the scouting and residential camp communities—with specific documentation placing it at Camp Woodland Trails in the 1980s and with Boy Scout Troop 390—as a highly competitive dining hall or campfire activity.12 The underlying ethnomusicological trend here suggests that the song acts as a social equalizer within the camp hierarchy. Because the tongue-twisters are inherently difficult to articulate, both authoritative camp leaders and novice campers are equally prone to failure, creating a shared, democratic comedic experience.14  \nThe lyrical sequence builds quantitatively from one to ten, with each consecutive number introducing a new, highly alliterative phrase. While minor regional variations exist due to the nature of oral transmission, the core structure documented across various scouting databases follows a strict alphanumeric escalation. The table below details the most common standardized phrasing alongside notable regional or localized variations, illustrating the geographical diffusion of the text.\n\n| Number Sequence | Standard Documented Phrasing | Notable Folk Variations and Deviations |\n| :---- | :---- | :---- |\n| One | One fat hen. | No known variations. |\n| Two | A couple of ducks. | No known variations. |\n| Three | Three brown bears. | Three baby brown bears.11 |\n| Four | Four running hares. | Four rapid running hares 12; Four rabbit running hares.11 |\n| Five | Five fiery felines fighting for french fries. | Five fat fidgety ferrets 11; Five funny flying flamingos 14; Five fat fidgety felines.12 |\n| Six | Six simple Simons selling six pies simply. | Six simple Simons selling salt in Siam 11; Six supersonic singing songs from Sam.14 |\n| Seven | Seven Sicilian sailors sailing the seven seas in a sloop. | Seven salty sailors sniffing snoose 11; Seven slimy sailors sniffing snuff 12; Seven silly students stirring stew.14 |\n| Eight | Eight eager embryos eating eight eggs eagerly. | Eight elongated elephants elevating on escalators.11 |\n| Nine | Nine naughty nunus knitting nine nighties nightly. | Nine nasty nematoids nibbling on nine nasty nimatoads 11; Nine no-good nunus who never know what to do.14 |\n| Ten | Ten tenacious tigers tying ten ties tightly. | Ten two-ton two-tone tan transcontinental trucks travelling from Tallahassee, Tennessee to Tyler, Texas.11 |\n\nThe variations documented in the latter half of the sequence heavily highlight the geographic and temporal diffusion of the oral tradition. References to the massive geographical spread of \"Tallahassee, Tennessee to Tyler, Texas\" suggest an American Southern or Midwestern colloquial adaptation, reflecting the logistics of the mid-century American trucking industry.12 Conversely, versions mentioning antiquated colonial terms like \"Siam\" (for Thailand) or the consumption of \"snuff\" (smokeless tobacco) demonstrate the retention of an older, turn-of-the-century vocabulary that has miraculously survived within the youth demographic.12 Because this artifact is an unaccompanied spoken-word chant rather than a melodic composition, it holds no musical copyright whatsoever, and the specific lyrics are definitively in the public domain, surviving entirely through the organic folk process.10"
    }
